In this proclamation, President Barack Obama recognizes May as Asian American and Pacific Islander Heritage Month. He acknowledges the contributions of Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders throughout history, such as Japanese immigrants, Chinese railroad workers, Native Hawaiians, and striving immigrants. The president also acknowledges the struggles and injustices faced by these communities, including exclusion, discrimination, internment of Japanese Americans during World War II, and violence towards South Asian Americans. He highlights important milestones in addressing discrimination, such as the Civil Liberties Act of 1988 and the repeal of the Chinese Exclusion Act. The president emphasizes the need to address disparities in healthcare, education, and employment that still affect these communities. He reaffirms his administration's commitment to equal access and opportunities and calls for commonsense immigration reform. President Obama encourages Americans to learn more about the history of Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders and to celebrate the month with appropriate programs and activities.